# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1920-chicago-american-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The **1919 Detroit Stars baseball team** competed in Negro league baseball during the 1919 baseball season.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In their first year of competition, the Stars won the championship of independent western Negro league clubs.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] While the Seamhead website reports that the team compiled a record of 27–13, the "Game Log" below includes 44 wins based on 1919 games for which contemporaneous newspaper accounts have been located.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars played their home games at Mack Park in Detroit with a handful of games also played at Navin Field.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The team was owned by Tenny Blount and led by player-manager Pete Hill who compiled a .396 batting average and .892 slugging percentage.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The team was established in 1919 by owner Tenny Blount (1873–1934), sometimes also known as "Teddy" Blount, with assistance from Rube Foster who owned the Chicago American Giants.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Blount was an Alabama native who moved to Detroit in 1913 and became a prominent "numbers man".
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In addition to the three Hall of Fame inductees, the Stars received strong performances from several other position players.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] First baseman Edgar Wesley, a left-handed hitter from Texas, compiled a .322 batting average and a .610 slugging percentage for the 1919 Stars.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In 146 at bats, he tallied eight home runs, 21 extra-base hits, and 43 RBIs.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Joe Hewitt, an infielder from Alabama, led the team with 153 at bats and ranked second with 36 runs scored and third with 36 hits.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Second baseman Frank Warfield, a Kentucky native, led the team with eight triples.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Sam Crawford was the team's leading pitcher, compiling a 10–4 record and 2.89 earned run average (ERA).
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] John Donaldson also pitched for the Stars, compiling a 2.33 ERA.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] Donaldson was regarded as one of the greatest pitchers of the era, appearing in approximately 700 games with over 400 wins and 5,000 strikeouts.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] He was voted a first-team member of the 1952 *Pittsburgh Courier* player-voted poll of the Negro leagues best players ever.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] During April and May, the Stars opened the season with a 13-game win streak, including victories over all-white semipro teams.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In late May, an all-white team from Wyandotte, Michigan recruited Detroit Tigers pitcher Rudy Kallio to start a game against the Stars; the Stars scored eight runs off Kallio.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The local semipro champion, the Maxwells, lost two games to the Stars in the first half of the season, then recruited major league pitcher Ralph Comstock to start a July 13 games against the Stars.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] With Comstock pitching a strong game for the Maxwells, the Stars lost their first game to a white team by a 4–3 score.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars played a total of six games with the Maxwells in 1919, winning three games and losing two.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars' principal rivalry for the western championship of Negro league baseball came from Rube Foster's Chicago American Giants.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Giants won two of three in a series played in Chicago in June.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] When the teams met for a series in Detroit in early July, the Stars won three games.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The also played a seven-game seriesin late July and early August that was billed as the championship series.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The Stars won five games to take the championship.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] As noted in the "Game Log" below, the Stars also played multiple series with other Negro League teams, including the Cuban Stars, Dayton Marcos from Ohio, and the Hilldale Club from Pennsylvania.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] In the last game of the season, the Murray All Stars recruited Detroit Tigers pitcher Bernie Boland; Boland held the Stars scoreless.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1919-detroit-stars-season] The following batting and pitching statistics are drawn from the Seamheads web site which appear to be incomplete.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-boston-braves-season] The **1920 Boston Braves season** was the 50th season of the franchise.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-boston-red-sox-season] The **1920 Boston Red Sox season** was the 20th season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished fifth in the American League (AL) with a record of 72 wins and 81 losses, 25+1⁄2 games behind the Cleveland Indians, who went on to win the 1920 World Series.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-robins-season] The **1920 Brooklyn Robins**, also known as the **Dodgers**, won 16 of their final 18 games to pull away from a tight pennant race and earn a trip to their second World Series against the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-robins-season] The team featured four Hall of Famers: manager Wilbert Robinson, pitchers Burleigh Grimes and Rube Marquard, and outfielder Zack Wheat.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-robins-season] Grimes anchored a pitching staff that allowed the fewest runs in the majors.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-robins-season] On October 10, 1920, which was the fifth game of the World Series, Elmer Smith of the Indians hit the first grand slam in World Series history.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-robins-season] On the same day, Bill Wambsganss of the Indians had an unassisted triple play.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-robins-season] He caught a liner, touched second base, and tagged the runner coming from first base.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-robins-season] During that same game, Indians pitcher Jim Bagby became the first pitcher to hit a home run in World Series history.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The **1920 Brooklyn Royal Giants baseball team** represented the Brooklyn Royal Giants as an independent during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team compiled a 13–7–2 (.636) record and won the Eastern independent championship.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] Nat Strong was the team's owner, and John Henry Lloyd was the manager.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team played its home games at Dexter Park in Queens.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-brooklyn-royal-giants-season] The team's leading pitchers were Harry Kenyon (3–1, 2.65 ERA) and Jesse Hubbard (3–2, 3.19 ERA, 41 strikeouts).
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1920 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 51–19–2 record (45–15–2 in NNL games) and won the first NNL championship.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] Rube Foster was the team's owner and manager.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team played its home games at Schorling Park in Chicago.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-cubs-season] The **1920 Chicago Cubs season** was the 49th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 45th in the National League and the fifth at Wrigley Field (then known as "Weeghman/Cubs Park").
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished sixth in the National League with a record of 75–79.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-cubs-season] (a) Not credited with an RBI for his home run, according to Baseball Reference and Retrosheet.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1920 Chicago White Sox season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The team was in contention to defend their American League pennant going into the final week of the season.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] However, for all intents and purposes, the season ended on September 26, when news of the Black Sox Scandal became public.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The team finished with a record of 96-58, which was not only the best record during Comiskey's ownership (and the best finish of the Gleason era), but would remain a franchise record for the next 44 years until 1964 when the Sox won 98 games.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] Owner Charles Comiskey suspended the five players who were still active (the sixth, ringleader Chick Gandil, opted to retire after the 1919 season).
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] At that time, the White Sox were only a half-game behind the Cleveland Indians, but went 2–2 over their last four games to finish two games out.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] They would not finish in the first division again until 1936.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1920 White Sox are one of only two teams in baseball history (The other being the 1971 Baltimore Orioles) to have four 20-game winners: Red Faber, Lefty Williams, Eddie Cicotte, and Dickie Kerr.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] Shoeless Joe Jackson finished third in AL batting average, and Eddie Collins was fifth.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] Louis Browns, the team was the first in major league history to have three players with at least 200 hits each: Jackson, Collins, and Buck Weaver.
[src:1920-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox became the first team to have four 20-game winners in the same pitching rotation.
